One Line Plot - Bar Chart

Walter Xie

16/02/2017

library(gg1L)
#getwd()

Bar chart

Load the example data model.test from ComMA package (We only use the example data, gg1L doesnt depend it), select Mac only in OS column, and display the first 3 rows:

library(ComMA)
data(model.test)
model.test.mac <- model.test[model.test$OS=="Mac",]
model.test.mac[1:3,]
##   model test performance  OS
## 1   GTR 1044    1.144838 Mac
## 2   GTR 1366    1.081676 Mac
## 3   GTR 1510    1.078596 Mac

Plot the performance score of each test in four GTR models, where the texts of x-axis were rotated, and also use verbose=F to block messages:

ggBarChart(model.test.mac, x.id="test", y.id="performance", fill.id="model", x.text.angle=90, verbose=F)

Adjust position of bars

Change the plot to stack bar chart using bar.pos=stack, and title to Stack Bar Chart:

ggBarChart(model.test.mac, x.id="test", y.id="performance", fill.id="model", x.text.angle=90, 
           bar.pos="stack", title="Stack Bar Chart", verbose=F)

Use both bar.pos=fill and y.trans=per to create a typical percentage bar chart:

ggBarChart(model.test.mac, x.id="test", y.id="performance", fill.id="model", x.text.angle=90, 
           bar.pos="fill", y.trans="per", title="Percentage Bar Chart", verbose=F)

Add something to bars

Add error bars

using aggregate modified from [the code] (http://www.r-bloggers.com/building-barplots-with-error-bars/) in R Bloggers:

myData <- aggregate(model.test$performance, by=list(model=model.test$model,OS=model.test$OS), 
                    FUN=function(x) c(mean=mean(x), sd=sd(x), n=length(x)))
myData <- do.call(data.frame, myData)
myData$se <- myData$x.sd / sqrt(myData$x.n)
colnames(myData) <- c("model", "OS", "performance", "sd", "n", "se")
myData[1:3,]
##   model    OS performance        sd  n         se
## 1   GTR Linux    1.157008 0.2867760 15 0.07404525
## 2  GTRG Linux    1.084187 0.1367728 15 0.03531458
## 3 GTRGI Linux    1.393784 0.6169104 15 0.15928558

Or summarySE copied from Cookbook for R:

myData <- summarySE(model.test, measurevar="performance", groupvars=c("model", "OS"))
## Loading required package: plyr
myData[1:3,]
##   model      OS  N performance        sd         se        ci
## 1   GTR   Linux 15    1.157008 0.2867760 0.07404525 0.1588113
## 2   GTR     Mac 15    1.184172 0.2100471 0.05423394 0.1163202
## 3   GTR Windows 15    1.176700 0.2283331 0.05895536 0.1264467

Calculate the lower and upper of error bars, where performance column is the mean.

lower=myData$performance - myData$se
upper=myData$performance + myData$se

Add the error bars to the bar chart using +:

bc <- ggBarChart(myData, x.id="model", y.id="performance", fill.id="OS", y.lab="performance", title="", verbose=F) 
bc + ggAddErrorBars(lower=lower, upper=upper)

Add values

Add their values (in the column n) to the bars:

bc + ggAddNumbers(label.id="N", hjust=0.5, vjust=2)

Add the calculation result to the bars, such as the mean of y values:

bc + ggAddNumbersFun(fun.y.lab=performance, y.adj=0.9)

Add lines

Add the red line to show y=1:

bc + ggAddLine(linetype = 2, yintercept = 1, color="red")

More Types

Load the example data reads.phyla, where x is one of genetic marks, and the numbers are eDNA sequences (reads) identified as the phylum listed in y:

data(reads.phyla)
reads.phyla[1:2,]
##                16S 18S trnL ITS COI COI-spun TaxaGroup
## Actinobacteria 958   1  301   4   7        0  Bacteria
## Aquificae        0   0   10   0   0        0  Bacteria

Percentage bar

This is a brief version of percentage bar, which uses melt.id=TaxaGroup to specify the column of groups:

pbc <- ggPercentageBarChart(reads.phyla, melt.id="TaxaGroup", verbose=F)
pbc$gg.plot

Abundance bar by group

Use melt.id=phylum to determine the value of bars (the numbers of reads of each phylum), but to group data and colour the bars by TaxaGroup. Use width and height in pdf to resize the plot. It can also use the estimated width and height from the function.

# add melt.id
reads.phyla$phylum <- rownames(reads.phyla)
ab <- ggGroupAbundanceBar(reads.phyla, melt.id="phylum", colour.id="TaxaGroup", legend.row=1, verbose=F)
ab$gg.plot

#pdf.ggplot(ab$gg.plot, fig.path="abundance-bar.pdf", width=ab$pdf.width, height=ab$pdf.height)
